  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2809407930" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2809407930" />
    <a title="earthshattering" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76215590-earthshattering"><img alt="earthshattering" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577989025p2/76215590.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2809407930?book_show_action=true">May 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="earthshattering" class="user" itemprop="url" name="earthshattering" href="/user/show/76215590-earthshattering">earthshattering</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2809407930" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5359474092079345342">This book is excellent. It is descriptive, exciting, incites wanderlust of the strongest and deepest kind, and is hilarious. Tahir has very dry, observant humor and I was laughing out loud throughout the book. It is such a wonderfully woven story and it seems too imaginative to be a memoir. The author is curiously distant from the book. He describes himself and his actions and reactions, but they are always muted and have little emotion behind them. It is a very curious way to write a memoir, wh</span>
  <span id="freeText5359474092079345342" style="display:none">This book is excellent. It is descriptive, exciting, incites wanderlust of the strongest and deepest kind, and is hilarious. Tahir has very dry, observant humor and I was laughing out loud throughout the book. It is such a wonderfully woven story and it seems too imaginative to be a memoir. The author is curiously distant from the book. He describes himself and his actions and reactions, but they are always muted and have little emotion behind them. It is a very curious way to write a memoir, which is typically heavy on the self-reflection, character deep-dive navel-gazing, and emotional state updates. It is refreshing to read a story-like memoir. This whole book makes me want to run off to India and hitch a ride to a countryside village looking for people to meet and talk to. One of the central lessons of this book is the necessity and joy of observation. So much is missed when you have blinders on and are focused on some end goal, when in reality the fun and the life is lived in the observation, in the unexpected things that happen while you are waiting for something else. This book reminded me of something I had forgotten since my younger years: that leaving space open for unpredictability is a great way to live life. Two of my favorite quotes:<br />"Much travel is needed before the raw [wo]man is ripened."<br />"How long is the course to be? How fast do you learn?"<br />I will always love this book and will definitely reread it to remind myself to get outside of a mundane and strict mode of life and thinking.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5359474092079345342" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

